Step 1: Calculate Return on Equity (ROE)  
• ROE is typically measured using the net profit over the average owner’s equity.  
• In this case:  
  Initial Owner’s Equity = 13,000,000.00  
  Ending Owner’s Equity = 11,598,563.11  
  Average Owner’s Equity = (13,000,000.00 + 11,598,563.11) / 2 ≈ 12,299,281.56  
  Net Profit = –1,401,436.89  
• Hence, ROE = (–1,401,436.89 / 12,299,281.56) ≈ –0.1139 or –11.39% (rounded to –11.40%).

Step 2: Calculate Debt to Asset Ratio  
• Debt here is taken as Total Liabilities. From the balance sheet, the Total Current Liabilities are given as 2,491,297.55. (There are no additional liabilities.)  
• Total Assets at end = 14,089,860.66  
• Debt to Asset Ratio = 2,491,297.55 / 14,089,860.66 ≈ 0.1768 (rounded to 0.18).

Step 3: Calculate Gross Profit Margin  
• Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue)  
• Gross Profit = 1,535,951.24  
• Total Revenue = 7,825,951.24  
• Gross Profit Margin = 1,535,951.24 / 7,825,951.24 ≈ 0.1963 or 19.63%.

Thus, the solution is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "-11.40%",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.18",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "19.63%"
  }
}
